      <hedline>
        <hl1>Clinton Makes His Last Hurrah</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>William D Stine letter disputes August 12 editorial on Republican National Convention in Philadelphia</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your Aug. 12 editorial ''Time for a Convention Update'' draws attention to the decline in public interest in media coverage of national political conventions. But a false dichotomy is suggested as the roadblock to any easy remedy to the situation: either return to ''the brokered convention,'' or accept the current process of having primary-selected party candidates, leaving the convention for anointing and vapid entertainment.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your Aug. 12 editorial ''Time for a Convention Update'' draws attention to the decline in public interest in media coverage of national political conventions. But a false dichotomy is suggested as the roadblock to any easy remedy to the situation: either return to ''the brokered convention,'' or accept the current process of having primary-selected party candidates, leaving the convention for anointing and vapid entertainment.</p>
        <p>Instead, the conventions could still be the place where delegates meet to discuss and endorse the party's political agenda. Coverage of debates on planks within the party platform would again focus the public's attention on the parties' proceedings.</p>
        <p>Platform debates riveted the attention of some of us in the past at convention time, and they would do so again.</p>
        <p>WILLIAM D. STINE  Detroit, Aug. 12, 2000</p>
      </block>
